	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It's not unusual to acquire a taste for other systems (kinda like in marriage, heh.) so don't worry.
<br />
<br />Er, actually, you might have something to worry about.  It's just like learning another language.  For some people, they can learn a new language, and it doesn't interfere with their old language.  Overall, it may boost their intelligence, even.
<br />
<br />Some people, however, encounter destructive interference, where learning a new language interferes with their use of the old language.  And both are spoiled.
<br />
<br />I don't mean to get all serious, but it could happen.
<br />
<br />Anyway, I had fun learning Z-80 when I had the itch to program for S*GA systems, and then when I had had enough, I went over to the PC-Engine.  Sometimes I even look at NES 6502 code.  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";-)" title="Wink" />  You tend to forget opcodes a bit, and which register is on what system, but overall, it doesn't take more than a few hours to get back in the mood of your favourite system.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


